Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the audit
Foreword
Taxes are the most important source of income for public finances.
One of the focal points of the work of the audit courts should therefore be the examination of this area.
This is particularly true for VAT fraud.
This alone will result in annual tax losses of an estimated €100 billion in the European Union.
Already at the VI EUROSAI congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants pointed out the need for increased cooperation.
This makes it possible for the audit authorities, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise the audit practice.
The value-added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation, as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, for the first time, the courts of auditors of both states examined the UST at the same time.
The relevant audit report was published in 2008.
Since UST fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, there is a need for close cooperation between audit bodies, which will enable a comprehensive assessment to be made of whether the measures taken are capable of effectively tackling UST fraud.
The two audit bodies decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of the turnover tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany report on the audit
1st Introduction
Examination number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of examination: (CZ) Administration of the UST (D) Bilateral Audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as NK), Audit
The aim of the audit is to:
(CZ) the UST administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. Furthermore, the procedures used by the financial authorities in the field of intergovernmental mutual assistance should be examined.
(D) The audit was intended to evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the audit bodies.
In addition, further examination fields - linked to the UST - should be worked on.
The findings should be compared to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.
The audit period was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period prior to the audit period until the completion of the audit.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The courts of auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to carry out an audit of the administration of the UST.
In the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspected cases involving intra-Community transactions,
Which made it seem appropriate to carry out a further examination.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two audit bodies made recommendations on the management of the UST.
The aim of the inspection was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented, and to investigate the suspected cases identified.
The audit also looked at other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of UST claims, and the UST audit of large companies.
In doing so, the Court of Auditors found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit
• Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
In the first audit, the auditors compared the registration procedures for UST in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended that the registration of taxpayers within the EU be harmonised.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of those who are required to do so.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.
The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate rules to remove unreliable traders from the UST system as early as possible, in line with their decision in principle.
The Member States reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in ECOFIN.
The aforementioned common rules are no longer included in it, and the two audit bodies regret that.
They still believe that such regulations are important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of the Summary Reports As a result of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to the Member States that the Summary Reports (ZM) should be submitted monthly in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community sales could then be reviewed in a more timely manner.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax (VAT) for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the levy to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the UST Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation only entered into force on 1 July 2010, which means that it has not implemented the obligation to pay the zm monthly into national law on time.
• Recommendation 3: Data matching of the UST pre-applications and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and a proposal to examine the merging of the procedures for UST pre-applications and ZM The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation issued by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange on successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level In the course of the initial audit, the two audit bodies agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches to a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in every EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States use different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - Eurocanet, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on Germany's participation in the "Risk Management Platform."
2. Audit of selected intra-Community transactions
During the initial audit, the audit courts had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or whether they had been explained differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the UST pre-filings (or UST declarations) or zm.
The audit courts selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The audits by the financial offices (FÄ) of both states were not yet completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and appropriate measures had been taken by the respective financial authorities to this end (including ex-post UST fixes or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Audit of selected, particularly high-risk intra-Community sales
The audit also included high-risk intra-EU transactions between EU taxpayers covered by the Eurocanet system.
Eurocanet is used to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Member States will be able to participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in Eurocanet. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of Eurocanet.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, it was not possible to obtain information about which suppliers with German UST ID would have been classified as high-risk cases.
The NKU found both normal business transactions and those suspected of UST fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.
The FÄ were only able to carry out limited checks on high-risk transactions, particularly in the case of so-called "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities work more closely together in order to be able to trace the nuisance of goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Germany, as well as a number of other countries, have rejected active participation in Eurocanet because, in their view, there is not a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German tax administration uses other instruments to identify high-risk taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with Eurocanet should be incorporated into the planned network for the fight against UST fraud.
4.Mutual mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental mutual assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
For this reason, requests for intergovernmental mutual assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany will be dealt with in the same way.
The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKU compared the statistics sent by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two audit bodies believe that a renewed discussion on the statistics at EU level would be useful in order to avoid any remaining inconsistencies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information about the UST.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both audit bodies believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should support the Member States in this, if they so wish.
5. UST test for large companies
The auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the UST audit of large companies in both states.
In addition, they collected information from the financial authorities with a questionnaire, which they considered to be important in this context.
It was clear that the situation in both states is different.
The CZ has a system for selecting high-risk cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on UST audits, balance sheet data, and profit and loss accounts).
As a result, the UST control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.
A special finance office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.
In Germany, there is no comparable system yet. This makes it difficult to control and analyze the UST control as a whole.
The German financial administration is focusing more on the selection of individual cases and is relying in particular on data from the UST pre-filings or UST declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
