4. Audit of the management of sales tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxpayers within the EU
In response to the results of the initial audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended adjusting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for the deletion of registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should more effectively reduce the risk of potential tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not delete the VAT registration of taxpayers if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law no. 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "UST Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to require the FÄ to be erased if taxpayers repeatedly fail to submit UST declarations.
According to the Czech UST Act, the FA can automatically delete the registration of a taxable person if (a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for this; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the UST Act; (c) the taxable person no longer meets the requirements for the tax liability.
The first examination showed that, on the basis of the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 must delete the UST registration of "foreign taxable persons" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay UST in the current calendar year.
The FA Prague 1 often did not delete the UST registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the time limit could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the UST Act, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
According to this, the FA has the power to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if, in the previous calendar year, he has provided neither taxable nor tax-exempt goods or services with the right to deduct VAT.
Recommendation 2
Monthly levy of the ZM
As a result of the initial audit, the audit authorities had recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council's directive, which shortened the time limit for issuing the zm to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the UST Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be surrendered if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with Section 9 (1) of the UST Act are provided to a person registered in another Member State as subject to VAT.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the UST for these services, as required by Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC as regards the location of the service.
Recommendation 3
Comparing the data of the UST pre-registrations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This recommendation referred to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically compares data on intra-community transactions from the UST declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the UST is an essential condition for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
For this reason, the fight against UST fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is evidenced, among other things, by a study published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the loss of VAT for the 25 Member States between 2000 and 2006. Based on the analysis of the available data, the tax loss for the aforementioned period was estimated at 90 to 113 billion euros, based on the fact that the EU-25 lose an average of 12% of the turnover taxes due to them each year.
The estimated tax loss for the CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State could not develop an effective risk management system (RMS) on its own.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (Eurocanet).
For this purpose, intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in Eurocanet were selected (see chapter 4.3).
The aim of the EUROFISC network is to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to identify fraud cases as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to assess the risk potential of intra-Community transactions.
ECOFIN Council 6 already approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008, and at the same time adopted the principles for the functioning of the system.
Eurocanet, developed by the Belgian financial administration in collaboration with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect high-risk transactions and identify entrepreneurs involved in organized UST fraud.
