4.2 Inspection of selected intra-Community transactions
During the initial audit, transactions were examined jointly, where there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether there had been any inconsistencies in the reporting of taxpayers in both Member States.
The two audit bodies selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection, in which the tax examination by the FÄ of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth €22,686 from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his UST statement, in which the period mentioned in the German tax code did not have a UST identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German sales.
Through international mutual assistance in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, according to German UST law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need a UST identification number in order to be able to benefit from the tax exemption for intra-Community goods deliveries.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that, according to the audit carried out by the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxpayer filed an additional UST statement declaring the purchase of goods of the above value, while at the same time asserting his right to deduct the same amount of VAT.
2)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased goods worth €12,561 from a German taxpayer.
However, he said he hadn't purchased the goods and therefore didn't explain it in his UST statement.
The German financial administration, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, refused to process the request because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of 15,000 euros.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain documents, the tax audit was inconclusive and the original tax regulation remained in place.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA received two spontaneous information from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, according to which the German taxpayer had charged the goods in question to a Slovakian addressee.
The Czech taxpayer purchased the goods from the Slovakian taxpayer and announced the acquisition in his regular UST statement for the month of October 2004.
3)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased a car worth €48,500 from a German taxpayer.
However, he did not declare an intra-community acquisition.
In addition, he had not made a UST statement since August 2004, which is why the FA set the UST at CZK 0 for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information provided from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the FA asked the taxpayer in March 2007 to make a subsequent tax return, which the taxpayer did not do.
The audit found that the FA had carried out further audit actions in this tax case in 2007, finding that the car in question had been sold by the taxpayer to a used car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA carried out an investment for the tax period of December 2004, imposing additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings over the assets of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be irreparable.
4)
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech tax payer is said to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) to Germany for a total value of 198 167 euros.
In response to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, it was stated that a tax penalty case was pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Federal Court of Auditors found that, at the end of the proceedings, there was evidence that the German taxpayer was involved in fraud.
Intra-Community purchases of goods were subject to employment taxes of €182 424 (for 2004) and €369 690 (for 2005).
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German tax authorities, a VAT audit of the Czech taxpayer has taken place for the tax periods April, May and June 2005.
On the basis of the audit findings and the information from the international exchange of information, the FA set an additional value of CZK 703 031 for May 2005 and CZK 726 551 for June 2005.
5)
Czech taxpayer A is said to have purchased a machine for a total value of €58,000 from a German taxpayer in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer is said to have delivered a machine worth €88,027 to the Czech taxpayer B. B, however, denied the acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that B had purchased the machine from a German company with a subsidiary in the CZ.
Czech taxpayer A did not specify the purchase of the goods from the aforementioned German taxpayer in its UST statement.
The German FA's response to a request for information under Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 showed that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine worth €58,000, but rather a delivery within the CZ.
In the inspection, the Federal Court of Auditors found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine was classified as domestic delivery after the completion of an operating audit, and that the UST exemption was subsequently refused.
6)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer is said to have delivered goods worth €11,600 to a Czech taxpayer.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA had made its assessment on the basis of a supplementary UST statement, which improperly identified purchases from another Member State, including those in the above amount.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that after receiving a reply to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the German FA corrected the German taxpayer's UST statement and set an additional UST of €1,600.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding UST investment there, an investigation is under way.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has not yet been corrected, as in Germany only the taxable person who has surrendered the ZM can rectify it.
7)
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German tax authorities in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the issue of the purchase of a car worth €47,400 by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
Following an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA fixed the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the purchase of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the registration of the Czech UST-required person had been cancelled because he had failed to comply with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA had sent the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has so far not corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax ruling.
8)
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxpayer supplied a Czech taxpayer with a total value of €33,205, which he did not declare to be an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the discrepancies.
For the first quarter of 2005, the Czech taxpayer repeatedly issued subsequent UST statements.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of CZK 134 273 in the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005, on the grounds that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the UST statements made.
9)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer delivered goods worth €46,854 to a Czech taxpayer.
For the same period, the Czech taxpayer declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only €14,856.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the Czech FA reviewed the actual value of the delivery.
With the German reply to this request, three invoices were sent, which showed a total value of the delivered goods of 31,998 euros, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the results of the audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors, following repeated warnings from the FA in January 2007, the Czech taxpayer filed a subsequent UST statement for the tax period in July 2004.
With this statement, the taxpayer at the same time asserted his right to deduct VAT, and his tax liability for the tax period in question remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial authorities in the CZ and Germany had taken appropriate measures (including ex-post UST fixes or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of high-risk intra-Community turnover
4.3.1 Results in the Czech Republic
Eurocanet can be an important source of information to identify high-risk taxpayers in the Member State of purchase.
In the CZ, the early warning information received from Eurocanet will be checked by the relevant FA with the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, the CZ has provided information on sales and taxable suppliers deemed to be at risk in the Eurocanet system.
Nine Czech taxpayers have been selected for the audit.
Which had been entered into the Eurocanet either as a supplier or a purchaser by the financial authorities of other Member States.
