Since the German financial administration was not involved in the exchange of data via Eurocanet, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German UST identification number were classified as risky by the German financial administration.
The audit found both normal business incidents and those suspected of carousel fraud or other UST fraud.
In the cases in question, the FÄ exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003,
For example:
• In examining the early warning information, FÄ did not identify any suspicions of high-risk sales.
The taxpayers in question were constantly monitored because their data was stored in Eurocanet.
• The FÄ failed to prove, on the basis of the accounting documents presented, violations of the rules on the calculation of the tax base and the UST, even though they found inconsistencies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relationships with letterbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual business transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the FÄ and could not be contacted.
