• What are the most common findings?
CZ:
- large taxable companies have unjustifiably taken advantage of deduction of VAT for related deliveries and services,
• which were not used for a business activity in accordance with Section 72 (1) CZ USTG;
• used for representation expenses in accordance with Section 75 (3) CZ USTG;
• due to invoices that do not comply with the requirements of Section 73 (1) CZ USTG
- Large companies subject to tax have failed to apply for VAT to be paid in accordance with section 21 (1) of the CZ USTG.
Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.
Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and UST special examiners do not provide such information.
Findings on the use of large-scale audits are not separately recorded by the countries.
However, the Federal Central Office for Taxation can evaluate the database of magic, in which auditors and tax investigators in the states have to enter the additional tax result they have achieved if a certain threshold is exceeded.
• Does the financial administration analyse successful audit fields and draw conclusions for strategic management?
CZ: Yes, for example, nationwide audits are carried out with regard to high-risk goods and industries.
Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.
Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and UST special examiners do not provide information on particularly "productive" audit fields.
With regard to the analysis of such information, its usefulness and the way in which it is continued to be used, there were differences of opinion among the survey bodies.
Some senior financial directorates provide such information to the FÄ, but it is up to the FÄ to decide whether or not to use it.
4.5.4 Comparison and Evaluation
As a result, large amounts of information are processed automatically in the CZ. Among other things, data from UST audits, as well as key figures from balance sheets, profit and loss calculations are processed in the system.
The CZ is able to control the selection of high-risk cases on the basis of a wide range of information.
The same applies to the evaluation and management of UST examinations in general.
The CZ is planning to set up a special finance office for large companies in 2012.
In Germany, the financial administration does not collect comparatively large amounts of data.
Accordingly, it is more difficult to carry out these tasks in the same way.
The focus is more on the selection of individual cases.
